Checklist
---------
- [x] I have been made aware that if my problem can be summarized as _"I've created or tried to create a media using Rufus, and ..."_, and I am not including a log, **this issue will be summarily closed**.
- [x] I looked at https://github.com/pbatard/rufus/wiki/FAQ to see if my question has already been answered.
- [x] I performed a search in the issue tracker for similar issues using keywords relevant to my problem, such as the error message I got from the log.
- [x] I clicked the 'Log' button (🗒️) or pressed <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>-<kbd>L</kbd> in Rufus, or used [DebugView](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/downloads/debugview), and copy/pasted the log into the section that says `<FULL LOG>` below. _(N/A — source-level report, no failing run.)_
- [x] The log I am copying is the FULL log, starting with the line `Rufus version: x.y.z` - I have NOT removed any part of it. _(N/A — see above.)_

Issue description
-----------------

Source-level, no log there's no failing run. Two bugs in the same
function, `sanitize_label()` in `src/parser.c` same root cause (a string
shift with the wrong length or the wrong tool) and a one-line fix.
Bundling them on purpose same function, adjacent lines, same fix pattern
two issues for two one-liners felt worse. Confirmed by
extracting the function unmodified into a test program (below).

**Bug 1 - line 1581, leading-dash removal drops the NUL**

```c
memmove(label, &label[i], len - i);
```

Missing the `+ 1` for the NUL, so the old terminator stays put and the last
`i` characters repeat:

```
"?abc"             -> "abcc"            (should be "abc")
"(Ubuntu) something" -> "ubuntu-somethingg" (should be "ubuntu-something")
```

Deterministic everywhere. Real input usually doesn't start like this, so this path is rarely hit - mostly a robustness fix.

**Bug 2 — line 1606, overlapping strcpy in substring removal**

```c
strcpy(s, &s[strlen(remove[i])]);
```

Source and destination overlap whenever the tail is at least as long as the
token - undefined behaviour, and current glibc corrupts it for real:

```
"Fedora-Workstation-mate-mate this is a very long tail indeed 1234567890"
orig : fedora-workstation-mate-this-is-a-vong-tail-indeed-123d-1234567890
fixed: fedora-workstation-mate-this-is-a-very-long-tail-indeed-1234567890
```

The MSVC CRT happens to copy in an order that gives the right answer, but ASan flags
it (`strcpy-param-overlap`). The duplicate-dash shift just above (line 1596)
already uses `memmove` for exactly this kind of move, so the `strcpy` looks
like an oversight.

**Fixes:**

```c
// line 1581
memmove(label, &label[i], len - i + 1);
// line 1606
memmove(s, &s[strlen(remove[i])], strlen(&s[strlen(remove[i])]) + 1);
```

When it does corrupt the label, the lookup key is wrong, so Rufus matches the wrong core.img for that ISO
or none.

<details>
<summary>Test program</summary>

Build and run:
```
gcc -g -fsanitize=address -o test_label sanitize_label.c
./test_label "?abc"
./test_label "Fedora-Workstation-mate-mate this is a very long tail indeed 1234567890"
```

Only the includes, the `ARRAYSIZE` define and `main()` are not from parser.c.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#define ARRAYSIZE(a) (sizeof(a)/sizeof((a)[0]))

/*
 * Sanitize an ISO volume label or GRUB version, so that we can use it for bootloader lookup.
 * Note that this call modifies the string passed as parameter.
 */
int sanitize_label(char* label)
{
	// Notice: Do not add "-beta" to this list as we have existing GRUB lookups for
	// "grub-2.02-beta2" and stuff...
	static const char* remove[] = { "-i386", "-i686", "-amd64", "-x86-64", ".x86-64",
		"-x64", "-armhf", "-arm64", "-aarch64", "-32-bit", "-64-bit", "-32bit", "-64bit",
		"-intel", "-cd", "-dvd", "-standard", "-live", "-install", "-server", "-net",
		"-desktop", "-lts", "-studio", "-baseos", "-kde", "-xfce", "-lxde", "-gnome",
		"-mate", "-unstable", "-debug", "-release", "-final", "-stream", "-cinnamon",
		"-cinn", "-leap", "-tumbleweed", "-budgie", "-ws", "-iot", "-ostree", ".iso"
	};
	size_t i, len;
	char *s;

	len = strlen(label);
	for (i = 0; i < len; i++) {
		char c = label[i];
		// Convert to lowercase
		if (c >= 'A' && c <= 'Z')
			c += 0x20;
		// Convert non alphanum (except '.') to dash
		if ((c < '0' && c != '.') || (c > '9' && c < 'a') || (c > 'z'))
			c = '-';
		label[i] = c;
	}

	// Remove all leading '-'
	for (i = 0; i < len && label[i] == '-'; i++);
	if (i != 0)
		memmove(label, &label[i], len - i);
	len = strlen(label);
	if (len <= 1)
		return -1;

	// Remove all trailing '-'
	for (i = len - 1; i > 0 && label[i] == '-'; i--)
		label[i] = 0;
	len = strlen(label);
	if (len <= 1)
		return -1;

	// Remove all duplicate '-' (non-optimized!)
	for (i = 0; len >= 2 && i < len - 2; i++) {
		if (label[i] == '-' && label[i + 1] == '-') {
			memmove(&label[i + 1], &label[i + 2], len - i - 1);
			len--;
			i--;
		}
	}

	// Remove specific substrings
	for (i = 0; i < ARRAYSIZE(remove); i++) {
		s = strstr(label, remove[i]);
		if (s != NULL)
			strcpy(s, &s[strlen(remove[i])]);
	}

	return 0;
}

int main(int argc, char** argv)
{
    char label[256];
    strncpy(label, argc > 1 ? argv[1] : "Ubuntu-Desktop-amd64 24.04", sizeof(label)-1);
    label[sizeof(label)-1] = 0;
    printf("in : %s\n", label);
    sanitize_label(label);
    printf("out: %s\n", label);
    return 0;
}
```

</details>

